<li class="last"></li>
</ul></div></div><!--paging_filter--><p>The Supreme Court on Tuesday unanimously <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/post/why-ohio-early-voting-decision-could-be-a-big-deal/2012/10/16/a8c7d232-17bc-11e2-a55c-39408fbe6a4b_blog.html">rejected</a> an appeal by Ohio Secretary of State Jon Husted to overturn a lower court decision upholding early voting in Ohio three days before the election. The ruling was a major victory for voting rights&mdash;and yet another <a href="http://www.thenation.com/article/170493/fightback-voting-rights">defeat for voter suppression efforts</a>&mdash;allowing Ohio voters to cast a ballot when it&rsquo;s most convenient and hopefully forestalling the long lines that marred the outcome of the 2004 election in the state.</p>
<p>That&rsquo;s the good news. The bad news? Ohio Secretary of State Jon Husted swiftly limited early voting hours on those crucial three days to 8 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">am</span>&ndash;2 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">pm</span> on Saturday, November 3; 1&ndash;5 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">pm</span>&nbsp;on Sunday, November 4; and 8 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">am</span>&ndash;2 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">pm</span> on Monday, November 5. That means Ohio voters will have a total of only sixteen hours to cast a ballot during those three days. And before the weekend before the election, Ohio voters will still not be able to cast a ballot in-person on nights or weekends.</p>
<p>In 2008, the most populous counties in Ohio allowed more time for early voting&mdash;both in terms of days (thirty-five) and hours (on nights and weekends in many places). For the three days before the election, early voting locations were open for a total of twenty-four hours in Columbus&rsquo;s Franklin County (8-5 on Saturday, 1-5 on Sunday and 8-7 on Monday) and 18 and a half hours in Cleveland&rsquo;s Cuyahoga County (9-1 on Saturday, 1-5 on Sunday, 8:30-7 <span style="font-variant: small-caps">pm</span> on Monday). During those final three pre-election days in 2008, 148,000 votes were cast and &ldquo;wait times stretched 2 1/2 hours,&rdquo; reported the <em>Columbus Dispatch</em>.</p>
<p>But the reduced hours in 2008 are certainly better than nothing, especially since the elimination of weekend and evening voting between October 2 to November 2 will make voting on the weekend before the election even more desirable. &ldquo;This weekend is going to be very popular,&rdquo; says Ellis Jacobs of the Miami Valley Voter Protection Coalition. &ldquo;Ten of thousands of people across the State will take advantage of these days. In addition to making it possible for working people to vote in-person early, the extra hours will help take some of the pressure off polling places on Election Day.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Voting on the Sunday before the election will also allow African-American churches to hold their traditional &ldquo;<a href="http://www.aclu.org/voting-rights/take-your-souls-polls-voting-early-ohio">Souls to the Polls</a>&rdquo; voter mobilization effort. This is a big deal, since African-Americans comprised the majority of early voters in cities like Dayton and Cleveland in 2008, and were twenty-six times more likely to vote in-person compared to white voters in Cuyahoga County in &rsquo;08.</p>
<p>Early voting numbers for 2012 are still a bit murky in Ohio, which does not report the early vote by partisan affiliation, but early vote guru <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-p-mcdonald/early-voting-rising_b_1962843.html">Michael McDonald</a> says &ldquo;early voting is up quite a bit over the 2008 level.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s difficult to see how President Obama will win re-election without carrying Ohio, and how he wins Ohio without a very strong early vote turnout.</p>
<p><em>For more on the fight over early voting in Ohio, see &ldquo;<a href="http://www.thenation.com/blog/170448/ohio-secretary-state-subverts-voting-rights">Ohio&rsquo;s Secretary of State Subverts Voting Rights</a>,&rdquo; &ldquo;<a href="http://www.thenation.com/blog/169454/ohio-gop-admits-early-voting-cutbacks-are-racially-motivated" title="Ohio GOP Admits Early Voting Cutbacks Are Racially Motivated">Ohio GOP Admits Early Voting Cutbacks Are Racially Motivated</a>&rdquo; and &ldquo;<a href="http://www.thenation.com/blog/169284/ohio-early-voting-cutbacks-disenfranchise-minority-voters" title="Ohio Early Voting Cutbacks Disenfranchise Minority Voters">Ohio Early Voting Cutbacks Disenfranchise Minority Voters</a>.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p><em><a href="http://www.thenation.com/blogs/voting-rights-watch-2012">Voting Rights Watch</a>, our joint-project with Colorlines, is also reporting on voting rights fights across the country</em>.</p>
